{"cursor":"3003","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n\n\nIn physics, the term 'moment' refers to the occurrence and application of\nmoments in several different domains, which are associated with different\nconcepts. In principle it is defined as the perpendicular distance from a point\nto a line or a surface. Robertson, D.G.E.; Caldwell, G.E.; Hamill, J.;\nKamen, G.; and Whittlesey, S.N. (2004) Research Methods in Biomechanics.\nChampaign, IL:Human Kinetics Publ., p. 285. It is frequently used in\ncombination with other physical quantities such as in moment of inertia, moment\nof force, moment of momentum, magnetic moment, etc.\n\nIt is also used colloquially for different physical quantities that depend\nupon distance. For example, in engineering and kinesiology the term moment is\noften used instead of the more complete term moment of force. A moment of\nforce being the product of the moment of a force from an axis times the\nmagnitude of the force, i.e., F Ã d, where F is the magnitude of the force and\nd is the moment of the force. See torque for a more complete description of\nmoments of force or couple for the related concept free moment of force also\nknown as a force couple.\n\nIt may also be used when the distance is squared, as in moment of inertia. The\nmoment of inertia is the \"second moment\" of mass of a physical object. This is\nthe object's resistance or inertia to changes in its angular motion. It is\nroughly the sum of the squared distances (i.e., moments) of the object's mass\nparticles about a particular axis (I = \\int r^2 dm) . ''' Principle\nof moments''' Principle of moments is also known as the law of lever. This law\nis about objects balancing when the moments of all the forces acting are\nbalanced. A balanced object is said to be in 'equilibrium'\n\nPrinciple of moments state that: When an object is in equilibrium, the\nsum of the clockwise moment about any acting at a pivot equals the sum of\nthe anticlockwise moment about the same point. clockwise = anticlockwise\nF x d = F x d\n\nBy: Tafari Johnson In collaboration with Rodrick Duffus and Kevon Kirby\n","linknr":207,"url":"Moment_(physics)","recorded":1363137853,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Moment_(physics)&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Moment_(physics)&action=edit","//en.wikipedia.org/apple-touch-icon.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.wikihiero%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-head","#p-search","/wiki/Momentum","/wiki/Moment_(mathematics)","/wiki/Torque","/wiki/Classical_mechanics","/wiki/File:Cm_template_pic.svg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d4/Cm_template_pic.svg/151px-Cm_template_pic.svg.png","/wiki/History_of_classical_mechanics","/wiki/Timeline_of_classical_mechanics","/wiki/Statics","/wiki/Analytical_dynamics","/wiki/Kinetics_(physics)","/wiki/Kinematics","/wiki/Applied_mechanics","/wiki/Celestial_mechanics","/wiki/Continuum_mechanics","/wiki/Statistical_mechanics","/wiki/Newton%27s_laws_of_motion","/wiki/Analytical_mechanics","/wiki/Lagrangian_mechanics","/wiki/Hamiltonian_mechanics","/wiki/Space","/wiki/Time","/wiki/Mass","/wiki/Inertia","/wiki/Velocity","/wiki/Speed","/wiki/Acceleration","/wiki/Force","/wiki/Momentum","/wiki/Impulse_(physics)","/wiki/Torque","/wiki/Couple_(mechanics)","/wiki/Angular_momentum","/wiki/Mo